## Basic JavaScript Syntax

### Understanding Basic JavaScript Syntax

JavaScript is a versatile programming language that plays a crucial role in web development. It allows developers to create interactive and dynamic web pages, enhancing user experience significantly. As you embark on your journey to learn full-stack web development, mastering JavaScript is foundational. This section will introduce you to the basic syntax of JavaScript, providing a stepping stone to more advanced concepts.

### A Practical Introduction

Imagine you are building a simple web page that displays a greeting message to users. JavaScript can be used to dynamically change this message based on the time of day. For instance, you might want to display "Good Morning" in the morning and "Good Evening" in the evening. This dynamic behavior is achieved through JavaScript's ability to manipulate the Document Object Model (DOM) and respond to user interactions.

Here's a simple example of how JavaScript can be used to display a greeting message:

```javascript
let currentHour = new Date().getHours();
let greeting;

if (currentHour < 12) {
    greeting = "Good Morning!";
} else if (currentHour < 18) {
    greeting = "Good Afternoon!";
} else {
    greeting = "Good Evening!";
}

document.getElementById("greeting").innerText = greeting;
```

This code snippet checks the current hour and sets a greeting message accordingly. It then updates the text of an HTML element with the ID "greeting" to display the appropriate message.

